\begin_layout Section
Permutations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a set.
 A permutation of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is simply a bijection 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\, S\longrightarrow S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "permutations"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a set.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
(i) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 be two permutations of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Then the composition of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is a permutation of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
(ii) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a permutation of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Then the inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a permutation of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Follows from the well known results on functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "permutationgroup"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a set.
 The set of all permutations, under the operation of composition of permutations
, forms a group 
\begin_inset Formula $A(S)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "permutations"

\end_inset

(i) implies that the set of permutations is closed under composition of
 functions.
 We check the three axioms for a group.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Associativity follows from the general fact that composition of functions
 is associative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $i:\, S\longrightarrow S$
\end_inset

 be the identity function from 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a permutation of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
i\circ f=f\circ i=f.
\]

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 acts as the identity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a permutation of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Then the inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a permutation of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 by Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "permutations"

\end_inset

(ii) and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\circ g=g\circ f=i,
\]

\end_inset

by definition.
 Thus inverses exist and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a group.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "cardpermgrp"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a finite set with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 elements.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A(S)$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $n!$
\end_inset

 elements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
For 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

, this is obvious, since there are only two possible arrangements of two
 elements.
 For arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, we shall prove our assertion by mathematical induction, i.e., assuming that
 the assertion is valid for any set with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 elements, we shall show that it is also valid for every set with 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

 elements.
 Thus, we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 elements give 
\begin_inset Formula $n!$
\end_inset

 permutations, and we consider any set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

 elements, which we denote by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S=\left\{ a_{1},\ldots,a_{n+1}\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

Consider first the permutations whose first element is 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 To obtain all possible permutations of this type, we must put 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

 in the first position and then write down all possible permutations of
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 remaining elements; by assumption, the number of such permutations equals
 
\begin_inset Formula $n!$
\end_inset

 In just the same way, the number of permutations whose first element is
 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{2}$
\end_inset

 also equals 
\begin_inset Formula $n!$
\end_inset

 Thus, the total number of different permutations of the elements 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\ldots,a_{n+1}$
\end_inset

 equals
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n!\left(n+1\right)=1\cdot2\cdots n\cdot\left(n+1\right)=\left(n+1\right)!,
\]

\end_inset

 as was to be proved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Group 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "groupS_n"

\end_inset

The group 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the set of permutations of the first 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 natural numbers and is called the 
\emph on
symmetric group of degree 
\emph default

\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want a convenient way to represent an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The first way, is to write an element 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}$
\end_inset

 as a matrix.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 2 & 3 & 4 & 5\\
3 & 1 & 5 & 4 & 2
\end{pmatrix}\in S_{5}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we write a row with 
\begin_inset Formula $1,2,\ldots,n$
\end_inset

 at the top and right below write another row with the values 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(1),\sigma(2),\ldots,\sigma(n)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, for example, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(3)=5$
\end_inset

.
 With this notation it is easy to write down products and inverses.
 For example suppose that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 2 & 3 & 4 & 5\\
3 & 1 & 5 & 4 & 2
\end{pmatrix}\qquad\tau=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 2 & 3 & 4 & 5\\
4 & 3 & 1 & 2 & 5
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau\sigma=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 2 & 3 & 4 & 5\\
1 & 4 & 5 & 2 & 3
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

On the other hand
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma\tau=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 2 & 3 & 4 & 5\\
4 & 5 & 3 & 1 & 2
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In particular 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{5}$
\end_inset

 is not abelian.
 The inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is obtained by exchanging the rows of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem with this way of representing elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}$
\end_inset

 is that we don’t see much of the structure of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 this way.
 For example, it is very hard to figure out the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 from this representation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Cycles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "cycle"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 be an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
cycle
\series default
 if there are distinct integers 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},a_{2},\ldots,a_{k}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 1,2,\ldots,n\right\} $
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(a_{1})=a_{2},\tau(a_{2})=a_{3},\ldots,$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(a_{k})=a_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 fixes every other integer.
 More compactly
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau\left(a_{i}\right)=\begin{cases}
a_{i+1} & i<k\\
a_{1} & i=k\\
a_{i} & \textrm{otherwise.}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A two cycle is also called a 
\emph on
transposition
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{pmatrix}1 & 2 & 3 & 4\\
2 & 3 & 4 & 1
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

is a 4-cycle in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{4}$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{pmatrix}1 & 2 & 3 & 4 & 5\\
1 & 5 & 3 & 2 & 4
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

is a 3-cycle in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{5}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Now given a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-cycle 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 , there is an obvious way to represent it, which is much more compact than
 the first notation.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau=\left(a_{1},a_{2},\ldots,a_{k}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the two examples above become,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(1,2,3,4\right)
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(2,5,4\right).
\]

\end_inset

Note that there is some redundancy.
 For example, obviously
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(2,5,4\right)=\left(5,4,2\right)=\left(4,2,5\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "orderofcycle"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\left(a_{1},a_{2},\ldots,a_{k}\right)$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-cycle.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 has order 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We can write 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{j+1}=\tau^{j}\left(a_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq j<k$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{k}\left(a_{1}\right)=a_{1}$
\end_inset

it follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\tau^{k}\left(a_{j+1}\right) & = & \tau^{k}\left(\tau^{j}\left(a_{1}\right)\right)\\
 & = & \tau^{j}\left(\tau^{k}\left(a_{1}\right)\right)\\
 & = & \tau^{j}\left(a_{1}\right)\\
 & = & a_{j+1.}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{k}$
\end_inset

 is the identity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
If 
\begin_inset Formula $0<l<k$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{l}$
\end_inset

 is not the identity since 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{l}\left(a_{1}\right)=a_{l+1}\neq a_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "disjointcyclescommute"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=\left(a_{1},a_{2},\ldots,a_{k}\right)$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\left(b_{1},b_{2},\ldots,b_{j}\right)$
\end_inset

be disjoint cyles i.e., the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\left\{ a_{1},a_{2},\ldots,a_{k}\right\} $
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\left\{ b_{1},b_{2},\ldots,b_{j}\right\} $
\end_inset

are disjoint.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\tau=\tau\sigma.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We verify that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\sigma\tau\right)\left(i\right)=\left(\tau\sigma\right)\left(i\right)$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\left\{ 1,2,\ldots,n\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\sigma\tau\right)\left(i\right)=\begin{cases}
\sigma\left(i\right) & i\in A\\
\tau\left(i\right) & i\in B\\
i & \textrm{otherwise}
\end{cases}\qquad\left(\tau\sigma\right)\left(i\right)=\begin{cases}
\sigma\left(i\right) & i\in A\\
\tau\left(i\right) & i\in B\\
i & \textrm{otherwise.}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "cycledecomposition"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 be any element of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 may be expressed as a product of disjoint cycles.
 This factorisation is unique up to order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Existence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

is the identity then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma=\begin{pmatrix}1 & 2 & \cdots & n\\
1 & 2 & \cdots & n
\end{pmatrix}=\left(1\right)\left(2\right)\cdots\left(n\right).
\]

\end_inset

Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is a non-trivial permutation of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 We will show that there exists a cycle 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{1},\ldots,a_{j})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\{a_{k}\,\colon\,1\le k\le j\}\subseteq\{k\,\colon\,1\le k\le n\}
\]

\end_inset

 and a permutation 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\sigma & = & (a_{1},\ldots a_{j})\circ\tau\\
\tau(a_{k}) & = & a_{k},\;1\leq k\leq j.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Since the permutation is not trivial, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(i)\neq i$
\end_inset

.
 Chose the smallest such 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Define a sequence inductively as follows: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
a_{1} & = & i\\
a_{k+1} & = & \sigma(a_{k}),\ k\geq1.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Consider the set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\{ a_{k}\,\colon\, k\in\boldsymbol{\mathbf{N}}\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

As there are only finitely many integers between 1 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, we must have some repetitions, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}=a_{j}$
\end_inset

 , for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k<j$
\end_inset

.
 Pick the smallest 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 for which this happens.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
We will show that 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $k\neq1$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma\left(a_{k-1}\right)=a_{k}=a_{j}=\sigma\left(a_{j-1}\right).
\]

\end_inset

As 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is injective, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k-1}=a_{j-1}$
\end_inset

.
 But this contradicts our choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 be the 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

-cycle 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{1},\ldots,a_{j})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\rho^{-1}\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau(a_{k})=a_{k},\;1\leq k\leq j.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
This shows that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma=\rho\tau=(a_{1},\ldots a_{j})\circ\tau.
\]

\end_inset

Now by an obvious induction, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is a product of 
\begin_inset Formula $m-1$
\end_inset

 disjoint cycles 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{2},\rho_{3},\ldots,\rho_{m}$
\end_inset

 which fixes the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ a_{1},a_{2},\ldots,a_{j}\right\} .$
\end_inset

 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma=\rho\tau=\rho_{1}\rho_{2}\ldots\rho_{m},
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1}=\rho.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof

\series bold
Uniqueness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma=\rho_{1}\rho_{2}\ldots\rho_{m}=\tau_{1}\tau_{2}\ldots\tau_{l}
\]

\end_inset

are two factorization of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 into disjoint cycles.
 We may assume that there are no 1-cycles because they can be cancelled
 from both the sides.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1}\left(i\right)=j$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j.$
\end_inset

 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{k}\left(i\right)\neq i$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 By disjointness, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{k}\left(i\right)=j=\rho_{1}\left(i\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly we can show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1}\left(j\right)=\tau_{k}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\left(j\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Continuing this way, we get 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{1}=\tau_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Now cancel these terms from both sides and proceed by induction.
\end_layout

