\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

 and consider 
\begin_inset Formula $ghg^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $h=I$
\end_inset

 then it is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $ghg^{-1}=I\in H$
\end_inset

.
 So suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $h=R$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
ghg^{-1} & = & F_{1}RF_{1}\\
 & = & R^{2}\in H.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Similarly, if 
\begin_inset Formula $h=R^{2}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $ghg^{-1}=R\in H$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is normal in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Now suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $h=F_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g=R$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
ghg^{-1} & = & RF_{1}R\\
 & = & F_{2}\not\neq F_{1}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is not abelian.
