\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group, 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 a normal subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 be any subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 be the canonical homomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $G/N$
\end_inset

.
 A natural question is what is 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(H)$
\end_inset

? If 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 then the answer is simple 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(H)=H/N$
\end_inset

.
 What if 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 does not contain 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

? The answer is given by the 
\emph on
second isomorphism theorem
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "secondiso"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a group, 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 a normal subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 be any subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 be the canonical homomorphism from 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $G/N$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(H)=\left(HN\right)/N$
\end_inset

 and is isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $H/\left(H\cap N\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The image of 
\begin_inset Formula $HN$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 are same under 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(hn)=\pi(h)\pi(n)=\pi(h)$
\end_inset

.
 Also 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is a normal subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $HN$
\end_inset

 and the restriction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $HN$
\end_inset

 is also a homomorphism with kernel 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 By the first isomorphism theorem 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(H)=\pi(HN)=\left(HN\right)/N$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The restriction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is a homomorphism with kernel 
\begin_inset Formula $H\cap N$
\end_inset

.
 Again by the first isomorphism theorem 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(H)$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $H/\left(H\cap N\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This completes the proof.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
The basic idea of the proof is to ``count'' the number of distinct cosets
 
\begin_inset Formula $hN$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to verify that any such coset is a member of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(HN\right)/N$
\end_inset

 as well as 
\begin_inset Formula $H/\left(H\cap N\right)$
\end_inset

 and vice-versa.
 For example if 
\begin_inset Formula $gN=hN$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $g=g\circ e$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\subset HN$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
We can give an alternate proof by defining 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\colon H\to\left(HN\right)/N$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\left(h\right)=hN$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to verify that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is a surjective homomorphism with kernel 
\begin_inset Formula $H\cap N$
\end_inset

.
 The rest follows from the first isomorphism theorem.
\end_layout

