\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We know that image of subgroup is subgroup of image.
 What about normal subgroups? Is image of normal subgroup normal in image
 ? Or Inverse image of normal is normal in G?.
 After we answer these questions, you should wonder if there is any relation
 between the quotient in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and the quotient in 
\begin_inset Formula $G/N$
\end_inset

.
 The answer to first question is a resounding yes and the answer to the
 second question is provided by the 
\emph on
Third Isomorphism Theorem
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "normalityimage"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 be a normal subgroup of a group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 be a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 that contains 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 .
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $H/N$
\end_inset

 is normal in 
\begin_inset Formula $G/N$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is normal in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is normal in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $gN(H/N)(gN)^{-1}\in G/N.$
\end_inset

 An element of this set is: 
\begin_inset Formula $(gN)(hN)(g^{-1}N)=ghg^{-1}N$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is normal in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, for each 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

 there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $h'\in H$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ghg^{-1}=h'$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $(gN)(hN)(g^{-1}N)=h'N$
\end_inset

, which is in 
\begin_inset Formula $H/N$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $gN(H/N)(gN)^{-1}\subseteq H/N$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $H/N$
\end_inset

 is normal in 
\begin_inset Formula $G/N$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Now suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $H/N$
\end_inset

 is normal in 
\begin_inset Formula $G/N$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $(gN)(H/N)(gN)^{-1}\subseteq H/N$
\end_inset

.
 Then for each 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(gN)(hN)(g^{-1}N)=h'N$
\end_inset

, for some 
\begin_inset Formula $h'\in H$
\end_inset

, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $ghg^{-1}N=h'N$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Thus for every 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in N$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $ghg^{-1}n=h'n'$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $n'\in N$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $ghg^{-1}=h'n'n^{-1}$
\end_inset

, which is in 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 (since 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

).
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 was any element of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $gHg^{-1}\subseteq H$
\end_inset

 so 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is normal.
\end_layout

